  		<h4>Week 18</h4>
  		<p><b>Baby : </b>The baby now  reaching weighs over 100 g (3.5 oz). Outwardly, the baby is a fully looking like  human shape from head to toe, a cute little doll.  Most of all organs and tissues arrived and it's growth and  development continue.  The brain is continuing developing, with its new neurons. Synapses are being built, the cerebral cortex is becoming more complex, and brain folds are forming.</p>
  		<p>The baby’s movements are becoming more coordinated. It can reflexly move its arms and legs when touch and push the uterine walls. </p>
  		<p>The baby still has enough room to move around and flip over. But soon the uterus will be stretched to its limit and the baby will curl itself into a comfortable ball. By week 18, many moms already feel these movements, though they are rare and light. </p>
  		<p>Its soft bones are gradually becoming enriched with calcium and hardening, starting with the legs, collarbone, and fingers. Immune function has improved. By week 18, the thymus is on board, and the baby’s body can now withstand a number of infections.</p>

  		<p><b>Mom : </b>As your baby gets bigger, you may notice stronger movements and maybe even kicks in the weeks to come. Because each mom is different, you may feel this movement earlier (this is common if this is not your first baby) or in some cases even later. So, even if you don’t feel any movement at 18 weeks pregnant, there is no need to worry. </p>
  		<p>At this stage of your pregnancy, your body is going through a lot of circulation changes, such as increased blood volume and rapidly expanding blood vessels, which can cause your blood pressure to drop. This can leave you feeling lightheaded if you’re not getting enough blood flow to your head and upper body. </p>
  		<p>You may also notice around 18 weeks that your feet are getting bigger. A part of this is due to swelling caused by water retention, known as edema, which can occur from the second trimester onward. </p>
  		<p>Hormones also play a part in growing feet. The pregnancy hormone relaxin, which relaxes your pelvic joints so your baby can fit through the birth canal, loosens the ligaments in your feet, causing the foot bones to spread. You can relieve the swelling with a footbath of cool water and by keeping your feet raised; don’t worry (and have fun!) if you need to head out shoe shopping for a bigger size. </p>
  		<p>If this is your first pregnancy, you may feel the baby begin to move inside your belly sometime soon. This fluttering feeling is known as quickening.</p>

  		<p><b>Tips : </b>Take a diet rich in omega-3 fatty acids.  Omega-3s help your little one’s nervous system develop, and they may also help boost your immune system and reduce the symptoms of depression. Foods that are rich in this nutrient, for non vegetarian salmon or other fatty fish, or from vegetarian sources like flaxseed, broccoli, or walnuts. </p>
  		<p>It is a myth that you have to take food for 2 baby and you.</p>
  		<p>Yes it is true that during pregnancy calorie intake should be increased but it should not be doubled to support your health and baby's growth Once you reach the second trimester, this could be an extra 300 calories , on top of an average 2,000 calories a day. You can check your pregnancy weight gain regularly.</p>
  		<p>Everyone behave as doctor and started giving you  advise they might be scientifically proved and beneficial but most of times it may be harmful.</p>
  		<p>These unsolicited opinions can be annoying, try to take them in stride. You don't have to explain yourself to anyone. A simple "Thanks, I'll keep that in mind" should do the trick. Understand these people caring  and excited for you </p>
  		<p>Yes, at 18 weeks baby can respond.</p>
  		<p>Set aside time to interact with the baby by reading stories, singing songs, or just talking. The baby is listening intently to external sounds and is itself constantly surrounded by noise: mom’s heartbeat, the thrumming of blood through blood vessels, and the noise the small intestines and lungs generate as they work.</p>

