		<p>Now your posture and gait will change, as the lower abdomen protruding and pelvic ligaments and joints relaxing to adjust the expansion of uterus for baby. Your lower back arches forward, your center of gravity shifts, and you may find yourself waddling gait to stay comfortable. The hormone relaxin stretches and softens the pubic joint (or pubis symphysis), and the pelvic bones move apart. It may causes pain and discomfort, it’s worth talking to your doctor. Changes in your posture can lead to back pain, as muscles unaccustomed to strain adapt to their new role. You can prevent or alleviate this pain with low-intensity therapeutic exercise, prenatal yoga, or swimming.</p>
		<p>As baby grows and increase  demand of various nutrients: calcium, magnesium, and vitamins that creates it's deficiencies that leads to calf cramps , so consult  with your doctor, you can adjust your diet or add a multivitamin.</p>
		<p><b>Braxton-Hicks contractions : </b>At 20 week or after 20 week you may feel tightening of abdomen without pain. This is most commonly Braxton-Hicks contractions (or false labor)  as your body begins its early preparations for labor. These contractions are usually mild, unpredictable, and don't get tense about this contraction.</p>
		<p>Sometimes you’ll get a few contractions from sitting in a weird position, walking around too much, or being dehydrated. Lying down and drinking water should quell stronger ones.</p>
		<p>If you notice pain or can time these contractions at regular intervals, contact your doctor. It could be a sign of preterm labor, which is a potentially serious complication.</p>

